ons":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10451/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10451/canvas/1/696bd68f-c039-43d8-b7a6-7bd53fc9ac81","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T18:30:06.221Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Alma’s comparison of the Princess to a “sculpture of some kind” recalls both Alma’s claim that she can stand longer than anyone else for Reynolds (that is, she can tolerate his demands and be an equal to him in their relationship) and her own association with the sculpture in the fitting room. Alma wishes to be the sculpture turned to life from the Pygmalion myth and feels jealous of the Princess.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10451/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:673.3027522935787,135.87729357798167,644.4810779816513,751.0106077981652"}}}]}]}]}